}{\plain \fs32 \b\cf3\fs32 OVERVIEW  OF   THE MAP\'92S  ERA  HISTORIC  EVENTS.}{\plain \fs24 \ul\cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \b\cf3\fs28 The early years of railroading.}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The railroading era in the Austrian Monarchy started with the opening of a horse drawn carriage (on rails) line \softline
between the Edelbrucker Schlucht (Upper Austria) and Budweis on Nov. 2, 1827. Several others had followed \softline
by the mid 1830's connecting Linz (Upper Austria) to Budweis and Gmunden.}{\plain \fs24 \ul\cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \ul\cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The start of the steam railroad era began with the founding of the Kaiser-Ferdinand-Nordbahn or just Nordbahn \softline
as it was called, in 1836. All railroads starting shortly thereafter were of private initiative. This however also \softline
created some very unfortunate situations. Speculators, using the goodwill of other investors and the public, \softline
created an atmosphere of mistrust and uncertainty.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The Monarchy therefore found it necessary to create a new charter and invoked this charter on Dec. 19, 1841, \softline
making the construction of all new rail lines and the existing strategic and economically important rail lines, \softline
state property. The first of such new state railways was the Lombardisch-Venetianische Staatsbahn.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \b\cf3\fs28 The Revolution of 1848.}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 During 1848 a series of revolutions broke out in quick succession across Europe. The main causes were the \softline
economic depression of the time coupled with crop failures over the preceding few years and a general political \softline
frustration felt by the liberal minded middle class and nationalistic groups.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The first outbreak occurred on Feb. 22 in Paris, driving Louis Philippe from his throne. In Vienna the news \softline
from Paris inspired demonstrations that drove the conservative minister Klemens von Metternich from office. \softline
Other nationalities within the Austrian Empire wished to control their own affairs. On March 5, Hungary gained \softline
autonomy and proceeded to draft a constitution, in turn the Croats organized in Zagreb to seek freedom from \softline
Hungary. In Italy where the expulsion of Austria had long been the goal of the Italian Unity movement called \softline
the Risorgimento, a Venetian republic was proclaimed, and a revolution in Milan (March 18-22) was supported \softline
by a new liberal regime in Sardinia-Piedmont.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 In June, Czech leader Frantisek Palacky organized a Pan-Slav Congress in Prague to demand equality with the \softline
Germans. On June 17, Austrian forces crushed this rebellion and a month later gained control of Milan. A \softline
constituent assembly convened in Vienna to draft a constitution for the empire. It succeeded in abolishing \softline
serfdom, but in October it was driven from Vienna by a working-class rebellion; its work was later repudiated \softline
by a new prime minister, Felix Schwarzenberg. In December the young Francis Joseph succeeded Ferdinand I \softline
as emperor of Austria and imposed a severely centralized administration.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 On April 13, 1849, the Hungarians, under Lajos Kossuth, declared their independence. Schwarzenberg called in \softline
a Russian army, and in August the Hungarians surrendered. That summer a Roman republic created by \softline
Giuseppe Mazzini and Giuseppe Garibaldi collapsed and the Austrian forces recaptured Venice.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 Despite a few lasting gains, the Revolutions of 1848 resulted in severe defeats for liberal nationalists seeking \softline
democratic reform.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \b\cf3\fs28 Post Revolution Era.}{\plain \fs24 \b\cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The resulting uncertainty and poor financial situation of the state, created hardships for the Monarchy. Even \softline
though the economic climate improved significantly in the years following the revolution, the state run railroads \softline
continued their decline. This necessitated the sale of all the railroads operated by the state. Between 1854 and \softline
1858, this transaction consisted of 1766km track, 530 Locomotives, 4696 Freight cars, and 745 Passenger cars.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 With the lure of many concessions and other incentives an effort was made again, to raise private capital. Many \softline
multinational banks responded, with the result being the founding of the Staatseisenbahngesellschaft (StEG) in \softline
1855.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \b\cf3\fs28 The Semmeringbahn.}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The greatest obstacle to building a railroad connection to the southern part of the monarchy were the mountains. \softline
For about ten years a railroad trip to the southern parts of the monarchy ended in Gloggnitz and for people \softline
trying to reach the northern parts and Vienna, in Murzzuschlag.  Both had to transfer to horse drawn carriages, \softline
for a treacherous road trip over the Semmering Pass.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 With the opening of the railroad between Vienna and Gloggnitz on May 5, 1842 the monarchy was requesting \softline
that the rail line be continued over the Semmering. It issued a royal decree on Aug. 8 1842 to that purpose. On \softline
Jan. 31 1844 the general plans for the whole project were presented by Carl Ghega to the Director of  State \softline
Railways, Franscesconi. With the opening of the rail link between Graz and Murzzuschlag on Oct. 21 1844 the \softline
southern terminal was also ready. However, political circumstances and severe doubt about the technical \softline
feasibility of the project, (there was no precedent for the construction of the 1430m main tunnel) caused the \softline
plans to remain shelved for another four years. It was actually the revolution of 1848 that stirred the project \softline
back into action.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 If one includes the work on the part from Gloggnitz to Payerbach, the construction of the Semmeringbahn \softline
started in 1848. At the beginning the aim was to create quickly a place to employ many of the unemployed \softline
workers of the period. At start of construction 5000 workers had to be transported to the site daily from Vienna.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 Strictly speaking, the Semmeringbahn was not the first mountain railroad. It was however the first mountain \softline
railroad to operate at such heights (898m) and to overcome an, at that time unheard of, height difference of \softline
457m. On its 41.8km of length it had 15 Tunnels (total length of 5.4km) and 16 large stone built viaducts (total \softline
length 1.5km). About 1.4 million cubic meter of rock was removed using explosives. For blasting only Black \softline
Powder, with its low explosive yield, was available. Due to Carl Ghega\'92s refusal to use iron or steel as \softline
construction materials, 65 million bricks and 80,000 stone blocks were used.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 With more than 20,000 people employed at the height of  the project and given the enormous technical \softline
difficulties,  very few lives were actually lost due to accidents. More than 1000 workers however died of \softline
Cholera and Typhus due to the primitive accommodations and living conditions. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 There was also much criticism expressed about the \'93Ghega Trasse\'94 by George Stephenson and the Association \softline
of Austrian Engineers and Architects. It was, so they said, questionable that the locomotives can manage to \softline
climb the grades the railroad was to be build at. Two years after the start of construction Carl Ghega called for a \softline
competition of \'93Mountain Locomotives\'94 to establish if those engines were suitable for his newly constructed \softline
railroad. All of the four locomotives (Wr. Neustadt, Vindobona, Seraing and Bavaria) fulfilled the requirement \softline
of pulling 140 tonnes with a speed of 11 km/hr on the steepest part of the line.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 The actual mountainous part of the railway was completed in 1854 after only five years of construction. On \softline
Oct. 23 and 24 the first test run over the whole distance was carried out.  The first scheduled train traversed the \softline
Semmering Pass on July 17, 1854. The line was designed for a 6 ton axle load and a train was limited to 140 \softline
tons. In 1860 the trip from Gloggnitz to Murzzuschlag took 2hrs 4min. \par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
}{\plain \fs28 \b\cf3\fs28 The Builder - Carl Ritter von Ghega}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 .\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 Born on Jan.10, 1802 to a civil servant of the Austrian Navy in Venice, he had a fascinating career. In 1819 at \softline
age 17, he was already Doctor in Mathematics and was employed as an engineer for the city works department \softline
of Venice shortly thereafter.  In 1835 he started to work for the Staatsbahn and in 1842 after the monarchy \softline
implemented a new agency for railroad development, he was made responsible for the development of railways \softline
in the southern part of the monarchy. After finishing the design stage of the Semmeringbahn in 1844 he was in \softline
charge of its construction from 1848 to 1854. Knighted in 1851 he died due to a lung ailment on March 14, \softline
1860.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \cf3 \par
